04633nam a22005055i 9780226612188DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20192019ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018050984  a97802266121887 a10.7208/97802266121882doi  a(DE-B1597)550072  a(OCoLC)1090540808  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aKF4552b.L483 2019 7aPOL0000002bisacsh1 aLevinson, Sanford, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDemocracy and Dysfunction /cSanford Levinson, Jack M. Balkin. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tPART ONE. Do We Have a Dysfunctional Constitution? -- tSEPTEMBER 29 , 2015 -- tOCTOBER 12, 2015 -- tOCTOBER 12, 2015 -- tNOVEMBER 1, 2015 -- tPART TWO. Dysfunction and the Rise of Donald Trump -- tAUGUST 1, 2016 -- tAUGUST 7, 2016 -- tNOVEMBER 26 , 2016 -- tDECEMBER 3, 2016 -- tPART THREE. Constitutional Crisis -- tFEBRUARY 21, 2017 -- tAPRIL 14, 2017 -- tPART FOUR. Constitutional Rot -- tJUNE 18, 2017 -- tJUNE 24, 2017 -- tAUGUST 29, 2017 -- tPART FIVE. Executive Power and Constitutional Dictatorship -- tOCTOBER 7, 2017 -- tNOVEMBER 6, 2017 -- tPART SIX. Conclusions -- tJANUARY 1, 2018 -- tJANUARY 5, 2018 -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is no longer controversial that the American political system has become deeply dysfunctional. Today, only slightly more than a quarter of Americans believe the country is heading in the right direction, while sixty-three percent believe we are on a downward slope. The top twenty words used to describe the past year include “chaotic,” “turbulent,” and “disastrous.” Donald Trump’s improbable rise to power and his 2016 Electoral College victory placed America’s political dysfunction in an especially troubling light, but given the extreme polarization of contemporary politics, the outlook would have been grim even if Hillary Clinton had won. The greatest upset in American presidential history is only a symptom of deeper problems of political culture and constitutional design. Democracy and Dysfunction brings together two of the leading constitutional law scholars of our time, Sanford Levinson and Jack M. Balkin, in an urgently needed conversation that seeks to uncover the underlying causes of our current crisis and their meaning for American democracy. In a series of letters exchanged over a period of two years, Levinson and Balkin travel—along with the rest of the country—through the convulsions of the 2016 election and Trump’s first year in office. They disagree about the scope of the crisis and the remedy required. Levinson believes that our Constitution is fundamentally defective and argues for a new constitutional convention, while Balkin, who believes we are suffering from constitutional rot, argues that there are less radical solutions. As it becomes dangerously clear that Americans—and the world—will be living with the consequences of this pivotal period for many years to come, it is imperative that we understand how we got here—and how we might forestall the next demagogue who will seek to beguile the American public.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aConstitutional lawzUnited States. 0aDemocracyzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBalkin, Jack M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311071194340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226612188423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226612188.jpg  a978-3-11-071194-3  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles